[1;35m=> <tuplespace>[0m

[1;36m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Bob recovers the durable tuples
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────[0m

[2;37m# `tuplespace.open` replays every `PayloadKind::Tuple` record from the keyspace into the in-memory BTreeMap, in FIFO order (big-endian seq encoding + fjall byte-ordered iter). Bob's `rd` goes through the same in-memory query path as always — the durable layer is write-through, not read-through.[0m
[0;36m[bob][0m [0;32mfmpl> [0mworld.rd(:room).data.name
[1;35m=> "Rusty Flagon"[0m
[0;33m@captured[0m [1;33mbob_room_name[0m = [0;33m"Rusty Flagon"[0m
[0;36m[bob][0m [0;32mfmpl> [0mworld.rd(:menu).data.ale
[1;35m=> 3[0m
[0;33m@captured[0m [1;33mbob_ale_price[0m = [0;33m3[0m

[1;36m────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Ephemeral tuple did NOT survive
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────[0m

[2;37m# The `:note` tuple was out'd without `durable: true`, so it lived only in Alice's in-memory BTreeMap. Bob's process has no knowledge of it — `rdp` errors with "no matching tuple found".[0m
[0;36m[bob][0m [0;32mfmpl> [0mworld.rdp(:note)
[1;31mError: Runtime error: no matching tuple found[0m

